<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-461-439  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 461 439.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  Sept 24 1990 v24 n39 p120(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>FCC extends reach of price caps. (long-distance regulatoryactions)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Anthes, Gary H.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The FCC requires the Bell regional holding companies to move fromrate-of-return regulation to price-cap regulation by Jan 1, 1990.andO;The FCC contends the change will lead to lower prices for users ofvoice and data communications services.andP;  Prices under the newregulatory scheme will be permitted to rise at rates slower thanthe rate of inflation.andP;  There is no industry consensus that thetelephone companies will behave in a manner that will bring aboutthe FCC's predicted results.andP;  The commission suggests that sinceAT and T is legally required to pass on to its customers savingsfrom reductions in local area connect charges, its competitorswill follow suit to maintain their competitiveness.andP;  Whether thenew regulatory structure succeeds in reducing the cost oflong-distance services depends on the telephone companies'achievement of predicted efficiency standards.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     United States. Federal Communications CommissionGovernment RegulationTelephone companiesLong-Distance Telephone ServicesPriceBell Regional Holding Companies.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>